The NSA case highlights the total absence of intelligence debate
How can we explain the contradictory attitude of the French Government, which on the one hand off in public by summoning the US ambassador on 21 October, and on the other the other prohibited the flight of the territory by the Bolivian presidential plane, on the basis of the rumor of the presence on board of Edward Snowden?
In my opinion, there are two levels of response from the French Government.
When François Hollande phones Barack Obama or Foreign Minister Laurent Fabius summons the US ambassador, they react to a real discovery, which is the scale of US surveillance of all communications in France.
Is it not surprising to read in the columns of Le Monde a few weeks apart, on the one hand, the reproduction of American diplomatic correspondence and, on the other hand, a condemnation of the NSA's listening to the Quai d'Orsay?
Would it not be like a vague hypocrisy on your part?
The journalistic approach is not a moral position, but the search for the interest and relevance of information that allows every citizen to form an opinion.
When WikiLeaks unveils the analysis by US diplomacy of political or other issues around the world, we consider that, given American power, this is an important insight.
When we describe American interception systems against French diplomacy in the United States, it is by no means to outrage us with this practice, it is to describe the world as it is.
Has France benefited from information provided by the NSA concerning terrorist operations aimed at our interests?
Can we forsake American collaboration?
The very powerful technological tools of interception by the United States, but also by France, have been officially established for a total of ten years, have been formally justified by the fight against terrorism.
Moreover, in this area, France and the United States in particular have established quasi-daily cooperation and information exchange procedures, which are described on both sides as essential.
For example, Mohammed Merah's presence in the tribal areas in Miranshah was reported to the French thanks to the NSA.
France can be led, for example, to transmit entire blocks of data about the Sahel region to US services, and, in return - as has already been quickly said - the Americans can give information to French people about other parts of the world.
Therefore, the substantive issue behind this NSA case is not so much the capacity or the right of countries to acquire interception tools, as the question of the total absence of a preliminary debate, particularly in Parliament, on the justification of such systems, the perimeter that must be theirs, and, ultimately, the question of infringements of freedoms.
What is the real risk of the United States? A deterioration in its image?
No matter how much we denounce them, I do not see how they can be punished.
The risk faced by the Americans can be twofold.
The first is when their allies -- and this has been the case recently - learn that their leaders, sometimes at the highest peak in their state, have been monitored.
This is the case in Brazil and Germany, two countries where diplomatic relations with the United States have been tense.
Another effect may be more economical: more and more European or South American companies are reluctant, in the light of revelations, to entrust their confidential data to US providers subject to US law, and thus to the NSA’s hold.
Finally, the vast movement of revelations by media outlets around the world, which is helping to start a debate on previously virtually non-existent intelligence surveillance practices, could prompt legislators, including US ones, to reconsider the powers they have given to their intelligence services.
