FAA: Air passengers can now use gadgets on board aircraft (but not make a call with their mobile phones)
Airlines passengers will be able to use their door-to-door electronic devices to read, work, play games, watch movies and listen to music – but not talk on their mobile phones – under the much-anticipated new guidelines issued by the Federal Aviation Administration on Thursday.
But passengers should not expect immediate changes.
The speed with which the change will be implemented will vary from airline to airline, FAA administrator Michael Huerta said at a press conference.
Airlines will have to prove to the FAA that their aircraft comply with the new guidelines and that they have updated the crew training manuals and the rules on the storage of aircraft to be in compliance.
The FAA stated that it had already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of electronic devices on their aircraft.
Delta and JetBlue are among the companies that have already submitted plans.
“Based on the plan, we could approve the extended use of electronic devices very soon,” the FAA said in a statement.
Currently, passengers have to turn off their smartphones, tablets and other aircraft as soon as the aircraft's doors are closed.
They were not supposed to turn them on again until the plane reached an altitude of 10,000 feet and the commander gave the green light.
The passengers are supposed to turn off their aircraft when the aircraft is dropped before landing and do not switch them again until the aircraft has landed.
Under the new guidelines, airlines whose aircraft are adequately protected from electronic interference will be able to allow passengers to use their aircraft during take-offs, landings and ground bearings, said the FAA.
Most new airliners and other aircraft that have been modified so that passengers can use Wi-Fi at higher altitudes should meet the criteria.
Laura Glading, President of the Association of Professional Flight Attendants, said she was pleased with these changes.
“Once the new policy is being implemented safely – and we will work closely with carriers to do so – it will benefit everyone,” Glading said in a statement.
We are frankly tired of feeling like “room supervisors” when it comes to this question.
But it will still be forbidden to connect to the Internet to surf, exchange emails and text messages or download data below 10,000 feet, the agency said.
Passengers will have to put their smartphones, tablets and other aircraft in airplane mode.
So still no Words With Friends, the Scrabble-style online game that was played by actor Alec Baldwin on his smartphone in 2011 when he was rushed off from an American Airlines plane after refusing to turn off his aircraft while the aircraft was being parked at the door.
And heavier devices like laptops will always have to be tidy because they could hurt someone if they flew through the cabin.
Mobile phones on board will also continue to be banned.
The regulatory authority for mobile phones is the Federal Communications Commission and not the FAA.
FAA may lift the ban on certain electronic devices during take-off and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, a national transport safety expert on CBS News, said that mobile phones were still considered to pose a risk.
"Mobile phones are really a problem, not only because they could potentially create interference with navigational instruments, but because we know, according to the FCC, that they could disrupt mobile phone relay antennas if they are used on board," said Rosenker.
An industry advisory committee established by the FAA to examine the problem last month recommended that the government authorize a wider use of personal electronic devices.
The pressure on the FAA has increased in recent years to ease restrictions on their use.
Critics such as Senator Claire McCaskill, D-Mo., argue that there are no valid security reasons for these prohibitions.
Restrictions are also becoming increasingly difficult to apply as the use of devices has become ubiquitous.
Some studies indicate that at least one third of passengers forget to turn off their aircraft, or do so deliberately.
The FAA began to limit the use of electronic devices in 1996 as a result of reporting on interference with navigation and communication instruments when passengers were carrying FM radios, the high-tech gadget of the time.
New airliners are much more dependent on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also designed to withstand electronic interference and approved by the FAA.
Airlines have been enabling their passengers to use Wi-Fi at cruise altitudes for several years.
Aircraft modified to accommodate Wi-Fi systems also with better interference.
The vast majority of airliners are expected to allow wider use of electronic devices under the new directives, said Huerta.
Today's electronic devices generally emit much lower power transmissions than previous generations of devices.
E-book readers, for example, only issue minimal transmissions when you turn a page.
But the transmissions are stronger when the devices download or send data.
Amazon.com is among those pressing for easing restrictions on the use of electronic devices by passengers.
In 2011, the company's executives loaded an airliner from Kindle e-book readers and flew it to see if there were any problems, but there were none.
This has inspired the members of the FAA Advisory Committee with mixed feelings as to whether or not the use of the devices is at risk.
Douglas Kidd of the National Association of Airline Passengers said he believed that interference from the aircraft was real, even if the risk was minimal.
Other members of the committee said that there are only anecdotal reports from pilots that indicate that aircraft can interfere with aircraft systems, and that most of them are very old.
However, the Committee recommended that the FAA allow pilots to request passengers to switch off their aircraft during instrument landings in low visibility conditions.
A group from the travel industry welcomed the changes, calling them common-sense arrangements for technology-enabled travellers.
“We are pleased that the FAA recognizes that a pleasant passenger experience is not incompatible with safety,” said Roger Dow, President and Director of the U.S. Travel Association.
Rules for the use of electronic devices on board remain in force in Australia for the time being
Australian air passengers will have to continue to turn off their tablets and smartphones during take-off and landing despite the US move to soften the rules on electronic devices.
The U.S. Federal Aviation Administration has left the door open to US carriers for a change of their procedures so that passengers can read e-books, watch videos, or play games on their aircraft during critical flight phases provided they are in "airplane" mode.
Passengers can already do this for most of the flight, but many people find it difficult not to have access to their e-books during take-off and landing.
Australian carriers are considering the decision that requires US carriers to perform significant work to meet the requirements, but have indicated that they do not have the immediate intention of changing their procedures.
The Civil Aviation Safety Authority also stated that it was reviewing the announcement but pointed out that restrictions on the use of electronic devices during critical flight phases were still in force in Australia.
“CASA does not have specific regulations governing the use of electronic devices by air,” she said.
The issue is regulated by aircraft operators to ensure that passengers maintain safety at all times and passengers are bound by safety instructions given by crew members.
Virgin, who had already told CASA about her intention to extend the use of her on-board entertainment system using Wi-Fi technology, was open to change, but said she would follow the regulator.
“We would welcome a revision of CASA that would allow the use of electronic devices because we really believe that it would improve the customer experience now that we have (from the on-board entertainment system using Wi-Fi technology) on our aircraft,” said a spokesperson.
Qantas said that it was currently complying with the current rules.
“In line with our current policy, electronic devices cannot be used during take-off and landing, and we do not have an immediate intention to change that,” she said.
The FAA's decision applies to US airlines.
However, we are still interested in the regulatory developments that could benefit passengers, and we will look closely at the FAA's decision and the reasons for it.
For US carriers, the impact of the decision will vary from one airline to another and will depend on the age of their fleet.
Carriers will have to demonstrate that their aircraft can tolerate radio interference from electronic devices, as well as review manuals, training equipment, hand luggage programmes and instructions provided to passengers.
“As soon as an airline has checked the tolerance of its fleet, it can allow passengers to use lightweight portable electronic devices, such as tablets, e-book readers and smartphones at all altitudes,” said the FAA.
In the rare cases of low visibility, the crew will require passengers to turn off their aircraft during landing.
