“There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon,” said Georges Bwelle.
We would have taken him abroad if we had had enough money.
Instead, Dr. Bwelle spent years accompanying his father to crowded clinics and hospitals, getting any treatment he could receive.
“It’s not easy,” adds Mr. Bwelle.
You can leave the house at 5 o'clock, rush to the hospital to be the first, and you're not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
People can die because they wait too long.
The situation has not changed much since Dr. Bwelle's father died in 2002.
In Cameroon, there is only 1 doctor per 5,000 inhabitants, according to the World Health Organization.
By comparison, the ratio in the United States is 1 doctor per 413 inhabitants.
And even if they could see a doctor, many Cameroonians would not be able to pay for the consultation.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line, and almost three quarters of the country's health expenditure is carried out in the private sector.
"The only problem they have is poverty," explained Dr. Bwelle.
And because of poverty, they can't enjoy life.
After seeing his father and as many of his compatriots suffer, Dr. Bwelle was determined to try to change the course of events.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his team of volunteers practiced more than 700 surgical procedures free of charge over the past year.
He became a doctor himself, working as a vascular surgeon at the central hospital in Yaoundé.
And he created a nonprofit humanitarian association, ASCOVIME, that travels to rural areas on weekends to provide free health care.
Since 2008, he and his group of volunteers have assisted nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, with about 30 people, they pile up in vans after attaching medical equipment to the roof and crossing difficult terrain to the villages that are most in need of help.
Luck doesn't always follow them.
They had to push vehicles many times to cross rivers or muddy tracks.
But when they arrive, they are received as a hero: the community organizes a party, sings and dances and offers them the best accommodation available.
In these villages, free health care is a good reason to party, and Dr. Bwelle – with his big smile and overflowing energy – is more than happy to join the festivities.
The next morning, the team began to receive hundreds of patients.
“We receive 500 people on every visit,” said Mr. Bwelle.
They sometimes live 60 km from the village, and they come on foot.
In this mobile hospital, various health care is provided.
Many people receive treatment for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others may receive crutches, a pair of glasses collected, or a free birth certificate – a document needed to go to school, but many poor families simply cannot afford to buy it.
In the evening, the team performs simple surgical procedures under local anaesthesia.
Operations are usually carried out in a school, a town hall or a house; after the procedure, the patient gets up and goes to the recovery room to give way to the next person.
With the generator lighting, operating room and sterilization of equipment, Dr. Bwelle and his volunteers work until the early hours of Sunday morning.
It's a greasing rhythm, but village musicians usually help the team stay motivated.
“They are hitting drums all night to keep us awake so that we can continue to work,” explained Mr. Bwelle.
On Sundays, the team returns to the city, tired but proud of the work they have done.
The group, made up of Cameroonian doctors and medical students, performed 700 surgical procedures free of charge over the past year, and it knows that their presence can make all the difference to those to whom they come to help.
One man explained that the free operation he had undergone to treat a hernia would allow him to work again.
“It will change my future and that of my family,” said the man.
In addition to supporting this itinerant hospital and working as a surgeon at the hospital, Dr. Bwelle also works at private medical offices around Yaoundé at night.
It is this second job, he explains, that finances 60% of its association; the rest is covered by private donations.
"I don't know when he's sleeping," said Katie O'Malley, a second-year medical student at Drexel University in Philadelphia and a volunteer with Dr. Bwelle's group.
He is still in the hospital or trying to find money for his association in order to be able to run these campaigns.
For medical students and nursing students such as Katie O'Malley, who come from the United States and Europe to join Mr. Bwelle in his missions is an opportunity for learning on the ground that they do not have at home.
“We were able to participate in operations to help with skinning the blood or passing the instruments to Dr. Bwelle,” explained Ms. O'Malley.
It's not something you have the opportunity to do in America when you're a second-year medical student.
Student volunteers usually pay their travel to Cameroon, and often arrive with collected medical equipment.
But once in Yaoundé, their pension, transportation and education are taken over by Dr. Bwelle.
"He's a hero, there's no doubt," said Katie O'Malley.
He gave his life for this association, and his desire to help the Cameroonian people was not about to die out.
For Dr. Bwelle, the relatively constant workload is not a difficulty.
Helping others to live happily by keeping the promise he made to his father is something that brings him immense joy.
“I am so happy when I do this work,” added Mr. Bwelle.
And I think of my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
Making people laugh and relieve pain are the reasons why I do this.
