Scientists have just shed light on how the movements of a dog's tail are related to its mood.
Previous studies had revealed that happy dogs swirled their tails further to the right (from the dog's point of view), while the nervous dogs moved it further to the left.
But now scientists say that dogs can detect these subtle differences and respond to them.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, said, "Everyone knows that in humans, the left side and the right side of the brain are involved differently in stimuli that arouse positive or negative emotions. ”
Here, we tried to see what happened in other species.
He added that, just as in humans, in dogs the right side of the brain was responsible for the movement to the left and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played a different role in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to disordered queueden queuings of other dogs, researchers followed animals watching films featuring other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the animals and analysed their behaviour.
It will certainly not be long before we understand why their tail sometimes goes on one side and sometimes on the other.
Professor Vallortigara explained: “We presented to dogs films containing other dogs – either a naturalistic version or a silhouette to avoid any other factors of confusion – and we were able to track the tail movement and present it as going further to the left or right. ”
When the animals saw an unspoken dog moving its tail to the right (from the point of view of the dog wagging its tail), they remained perfectly relaxed.
But when they spotted a tail narrowly to the left (again from the point of view of the dog wagging its tail), their heart rate accelerated and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said he did not think that dogs were deliberately communicating with each other through these movements.
Rather, he thinks that dogs know from experience the movements they should or should not worry about.
He added, "If you meet other dogs several times and if you notice that, most of the time, the movement from their tail to one side is associated with a more friendly attitude and the right side leads to a less friendly attitude, you will react according to that experience. ”
The researchers indicate that the results could enable owners, veterinarians and trainers to better understand the emotions of their animals.
Dog behaviour expert John Bradshaw, a visiting professor at the University of Bristol School of Veterinary Sciences, said that this was not the first study to examine the importance of the left and right in the canine species.
Last year, a team at Lincoln University discovered that dogs turned their heads to the left when they looked at an aggressive dog and to the right when it was a cheerful dog.
And in another scientific study by the University of Victoria in Canada, he said, "Dogs went easier to a robotic dog when its tail moved to the left rather than to the right, instead of becoming anxious – the opposite of what is in the Italian study. ”
He said that the differences might come from the fact that the dogs that participated in the various studies did not fully consider the animals of the films or the robots as dogs.
A study of how dogs react to real dogs might be useful, he explained.
“Although many of the evidence in different mammals indicate that both sides of the brain are used for different purposes, many details still need to be clarified – and dogs are no exception,” he said.
However, given the ease with which their behaviour can be recorded, it will surely not be long before we understand why their tail sometimes moves on one side and sometimes on the other.
