Early puberty: Ageing earlier
Studies show that African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach the age of puberty earlier than white girls.
Physical changes do not mean that puberty is imminent.
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are responsible
Experts believe that obesity epidemic could be a trigger for early puberty
The trend towards early puberty is not as pronounced among boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist specializing in family and child health issues.
Should a mother worry if her daughter's breasts and pubic hair start growing at the age of seven or eight?
At the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatrics this week in Orlando, Florida, Dr. Paul Kaplowitz, a polo denologist, explained that these early physical changes are quite common among young American women and represent a new norm.
“I spend a lot of time reassuring parents – in general, this does not indicate a rapid shift towards full puberty,” said Kaplowitz.
Clear signs of development, such as budding of the breasts, hair under the arms and in the pubic area and body odours, appear earlier in girls.
But there has been only a slight advance in the age of the early rule over the past four decades.
In the United States, the average age is 12 and a half, when it was 12, three-quarters in 1970.
“Once the chest has begun to develop, it takes at least two or three years before the first rules appear,” said Kaplowitz, also the author of “Early Puberty in Girls: The Essential Guide to Coping with This Common Problem.”
Time is the most accurate test of how puberty will evolve.
There is a debate about what constitutes the actual onset of puberty, but it is considered "early" when the development of the breast is accompanied by sudden growth before the age of 8.
In most cases, development slows or stops – this is something that a pediatrician can follow closely.
Faster evolution may justify tests performed by an endocrinologist to rule out serious problems such as tumours or cysts.
There are treatments to delay the onset of early menstruation and prevent other consequences: premature bone ageing that can slow growth and small size in adulthood.
Recommendations for drug and hormonal treatment are based on child age, developmental rate, growth rate and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is careful with drugs but acknowledges that "controlling puberty can alleviate some of the behavioral problems and the feeling for young girls to be different from others."
The other big problem is understandable: parents simply don't want their very young girls to have their rules.
“They fear the risk of pregnancy or even the way they manage hygiene issues,” said Kaplowitz.
"It was a shock," recalls a woman whose daughter had her first period at 10.
Even though there were signs and we talked about the rules, it wasn't emotionally prepared.
She returned from the school frightened and upset to be the first among her friends.
There are many theories brought to the attention of the public on the causes of early puberty.
Yet there is no consistent theory that hormones in milk or other foods, environmentally friendly chemicals, or media-sponsored sexual messages are responsible.
Boys, like girls, reach their puberty earlier.
Kaplowitz argues that the most credible hypothesis is the obesity epidemic.
He participated in a study of girls aged 6 to 9 years that links the percentage of fat to the onset of puberty.
Other findings support this conclusion, but there are many other influencing factors.
In this country, African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach the age of puberty earlier than white girls.
There are various explanations.
Globally, the mechanisms of early puberty appear to be influenced by everything from economic to climate to genes.
Another problem is that while boys have hair on their faces and in the younger pubic area, the trend towards true early puberty is not as pronounced as among girls.
Other doctors attending the AAP conference stressed the complexity of the topic.
The appearance of acne and pubic hair is common, even in infants and toddlers.
“We need to be careful about how we identify the true onset of puberty,” said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a child-endocrinomist working at Goryeb Children’s Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to ask their pediatrician for advice on how to talk to their child.
“This may mean having a conversation earlier than expected,” Kaplowitz explained.
If you stay calm, your child will generally react well.
Girls with early puberty must be reassured that, even when it comes sooner than expected, the process is part of life.
