However, the current economic crisis has been at a turning point.
The austerity imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank, combined with the straitjacket on national economies through membership of the single currency, has led many people to believe that Project Europe has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments with excessive budget deficits – this was true for Greece alone.
Instead, the European system has put exchange rates favourable to German exporters – what German politicians want to retain.
Without the possibility of devaluation of the national currency, the countries of southern Europe are left with a problem of intrinsic productivity vis-à-vis Germany.
The only recourse is to make drastic cuts in wages and public spending – encouraged by Berlin.
Beyond the current budgetary and monetary problems, there is a deeper productivity-related malaise in Europe.
As a result of the “green” energy policies imposed by Brussels – which are a reason to subsidize French and German energy companies at consumer costs – European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times as much for gas as the US.
This is a prohibitive disadvantage in terms of costs, as we have already seen in Grangemouth.
All wage freezes in the world will not prevent the European petrochemical industry from being penalised by cheap American shale gas.
As a result, the revolt is rife, particularly in France, one of the EU's great leaders.
After the war, the French political elite saw the EU as a means of controlling Germany and putting Paris on an equal footing with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a passport to its political legitimacy and has imposed its own economic policy in Europe, leaving the French economy struggling.
