A team of biologists led by the Wildlife Conservation Society of New York has identified a new species of humpback dolphin off the northern coast of Australia.
Thibaut Bouveroux, Scientist at the Observatory for Conservation and Study of Animals and Marine Environments (OCEAMM) returns for L'Express on this discovery and explains the long process of identification of new species.
Does the discovery of this new species of humpback dolphin surprise you?
That is good news, but I am not particularly surprised.
While in the past species have been described and identified on a morphological, anatomical and geographical basis, today the development of new tools such as genetics allows us to improve our knowledge of species classification science.
Moreover, it is not impossible that these advances in genetics and molecular biology will call into question the classification or belonging of a species to a genus, a family or even an order.
In the early 19th century, morphologists classified animals, based on morphological differences between species.
Today, some of these rankings are being questioned because of advances in genetics.
Similarly, two very morphologically similar species were distinguished by genetics.
This is the case of the new species that has just been identified.
About a decade ago, the scientific community recognized two species belonging to this subfamily: Pacific humpback dolphins and Atlantic humpback whales.
Recent analyses have made it possible to distinguish four species.
Why is this an important discovery, as the Wildlife Conservation Society has argued?
From a conservation point of view, it is essential to know these genetic differences, in order to protect the species and therefore its genetic variability.
While this population had been known for a long time by researchers, they did not know that it was part of a new species, present only there.
Therefore, if a problem of mass mortality caused by a viral or incidental capture epidemic arises in the region, we could be dealing with the extinction of a species, rather than a local disappearance of a population of a more widespread species on Earth.
This loss of genetic heritage would be much more problematic.
A species is considered threatened or endangered depending on the number of individuals on Earth, i.e. the stock, and the ability it has to recover from neighbouring stocks.
As for the species Sousa chinensis, from which the population of the new species is found, its stock has automatically become lower, making it more vulnerable.
Why is it rare to discover new species of marine mammals?
Marine mammals are located at the top of the food chain.
They live in homogeneous, open habitats, in which there are many genetic exchanges between populations and individuals.
This gene mixing limits the creation of new species.
Conversely, more closed ecosystems promote genetic isolation, which can eventually lead to the creation of new species.
It should be noted that the marine environment is the least well-known environment.
We'd rather send robots to Mars, than know what lives in the Mariana Treas, just 11 kilometers from the sea surface.
More money is spent on searching for life on other planets than in marine research, and it is high time that this has changed.
