Two YMCA employees charged with sexual assault following allegations against Jonathan Lord at a hearing of the Royal Commission.
Two employees of the YMCA of New South Wales were charged with sexual assaults against children following allegations against Caringbah educator Jonathan Lord in 2011, at a hearing of the Royal Commission on Sexual Abuse of Children.
But in its opening statement to the Commission, the YMCA stated that it “never had to deal with a problem of sexual assault on children within its organization”.
Director General Phillip Hare was questioned about two cases: a YMCA employee was charged with child pornography offences and a physical education instructor at YMCA Caringbah Hall was convicted of sexual assault on children at the centre where he worked in 1991.
Mr. Hare told Gail Furness, counsel to the Commission, that he was aware of the first case but was unaware of the second case.
He also admitted that the YMCA's opening statement was inaccurate, pointing out that “YMCA external controls were carried out and indicated that the safety of children was a top priority for the organization. ”
It was demonstrated to the Commission that the YMCA had been informed that it had received the lowest second reviews of four institutions at a quality audit of the Department of Education and Communities in August this year.
Mr. Hare, who started working at the YMCA at the age of 21, admitted that personnel management was a failure with Lord's recruitment and that he had failed to verify that employees knew that they were required to report any violations of the child safety policy.
Earlier in the year, Lord was convicted of sexual assault on 12 boys during his two years at the YMCA.
He was sentenced to a minimum of 6 years'imprisonment.
But Mr. Hare rejected the idea that the YMCA would have a cultural problem preventing staff from reporting Lord's breaches of children's safety.
The staff testified that they had observed certain shortcomings, including the fact that Lord remained alone with the children, kept them in private, made them sit on his lap, told them that he loved them and let them play with his cell phone.
Danielle Ockwell, who was under guidance from Lord and who had requested training in child protection because she was concerned about her behaviour, said she found YMCA Caringbah's child services manager, Jacqui Barnat, who designated Lord "very intimidating and difficult to approach most of the time".
The Director-General said that he rejected staff testimonies that they were reluctant to report such misconduct to their supervisor.
Instead, he stated that their friendly relations with Lord blurred their judgement, so they did not report his actions.
Mr. Hare stated that he had expressed his views with the New South Wales YMCA board that the organization's lesson from the “Jonathan Lord incident” should not be “reported” by staff, and the board agreed with him.
Mr. Hare said that the decision to have the staff sign confidentiality agreements shortly after the allegations were raised was taken by the YMCA Director-General for Children's Services, Liam Whitley.
He stated that the decision was intended to avoid contamination of the evidence, but that it was an “excess of zeal” and that it had been ill-implemented.
The YMCA of New South Wales was not a safe organization for children at the time when Jonathan Lord was employed there, between 2009 and 2011, the expert on sexual abuse of children, Professor Stephen Smallbone of Griffith University, told the Commission.
He stated that there were “serious problems” in the recruitment, monitoring, initiation, training and supervision of staff.
The hearing was adjourned until 20 December.
